  "text": "We demonstrated that microglial cells phagocytosed the prion peptide PrP106-126 A117V in its fibrillated form in a timedependent manner. We assume this uptake to be beneficial, as we could not detect any release of either cytokines or NO in cultures exposed to 10 mM PrP106-126 A117V. These findings contrast with other studies demonstrating microglial activation following 80 mM PrP exposure, which indicates that higher concentrations of PrP106-126 A117V might be necessary to activate an inflammatory response in microglia [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
